The Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton — This summer, readers around the world held celebrations marking the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series — Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (renamed Harry Potter and the Sorcerer’s Stone in the United States). They had ample reason to celebrate.
Since the young wizard first appeared on June 26, 1997, this "Boy Who Lived" has become a symbol of resilience and perseverance.
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, translated into more than 70 languages, and has sold a total of 450 million copies.
The eight films based on the book have earned a cumulative 7 billion dollars, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated an additional 7 billion dollars in revenue.
It is hard to imagine a day when global audiences were not captivated by Rowling's works for those of a specific age and with a literary mindset.
Therefore, I am always amazed when I recall my students' poor reaction to the book "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" in the fall of 1999, when I included it in the syllabus for my popular literature course at Princeton University. I have been teaching the "Bestselling Books in America" series since 1993.
The course examines popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to reflect on why and how these bestsellers have captivated their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask students to choose a final book that represents the popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first "Harry Potter" novel.
That year, the Harry Potter craze swept across the American coast.
In June, the American publisher of the series rushed the hardcover edition of the second "Harry Potter" book, "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets," into bookstores.
The institution also published the third book of the series, "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban," as well as the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone," on September 8.
By the end of the month, Rowling's novels had claimed the top three spots on the New York Times Best Seller list, while the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" topped the bestseller list for paperback books.
Time magazine even featured the glasses-wearing wizard on its cover.
Everywhere you looked, the image of Harry Potter was everywhere.
My students were eager to know why such a frenzy was happening.
Goodness, they were utterly disappointed.
In their eyes, the Harry Potter series was nothing more than second-rate nonsense, far beneath the cherished series like "The Chronicles of Narnia" or "The Lord of the Rings" from their childhood memories.
Although their childhood had only just passed a few years ago, they criticized "Harry Potter" just like many notorious adult critics: "fabricated," "poorly written," "clichéd," and "boring."
Goodness, they were utterly disappointed. In their eyes, the Harry Potter series was nothing more than second-rate nonsense, far beneath the cherished series like "The Chronicles of Narnia" or "The Lord of the Rings" from their childhood memories. Although their childhood had only just passed a few years ago, they criticized "Harry Potter" just like many notorious adult critics: "fabricated," "poorly written," "clichéd," and "boring."
In their eyes, Harry had neither miracles, nor wit, nor warmth.
The students' resentment surprised me, but in hindsight, it was nothing to be surprised about.
Although adults had always formed a significant part of the Harry Potter audience, these students were precisely at an incorrect age to objectively understand the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They had already passed the age to accept new children's books, yet at the same time were too young to have their own children (at that time I had just become a parent myself), and they were eager to insist that although the Harry Potter series was now immensely popular, it would soon be forgotten.
In the fall of the following year, that is, 2000, the next batch of students also chose "Harry Potter and the Philosophers' Stone" as their final analysis book, just like their predecessors, confidently rejecting the work.
Let's fast forward to spring 2007.
After putting the course on hold for several years, I taught "Bestselling Books in America" again.
When students chose the final analysis book, they chose "Harry Potter and the Philosophers' Stone."
And I was prepared to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This was a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who were not university students when they first read Rowling's work, but rather teenagers in their teens, just beginning to enter adolescence. This meant that they grew up together with Harry, Ron, and Hermione into young adulthood.
The same thing happened in the fall of 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto, not a label.
Will Harry ever disappear from memory?
As long as we are still alive, it is impossible.
Since 2010, I have taught a bestseller course twice, and in both instances, the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final presentations.
Are you tired of Potter?
From the reviews received on the "Children's Literature" course, where I taught Rowling's works, it is unlikely.
Now, I have chosen to include a Harry Potter novel in my syllabus, but I did not select *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone*, instead choosing *Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban*—this is the Harry Potter book I like best among the seven in the series, marking the transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, as it offers a complex portrayal of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also favor this book the most.
But how long can the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I teach Children's Literature, I start with a poll: "Which books on the syllabus did you read as a child?"
In 2010, 86% of them had read *Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban*.
In 2012, this figure rose to 94%.
But in the years that followed, the percentage continued to decline—87% in 2014, and dropped to 81% in 2016.
These are not scientific, I know.
But I'm curious: when I teach "Children's Literature" again next spring, will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80%?
Will the facts prove that the students of 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter's status is continually declining and will never become an eternal classic?
Is there still a balance point where the percentage can remain stable and no longer decline?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I was glad to invite him into my classroom.
